Results

1. Quality control of LC-MS data

To monitor the changes in chromatographic properties, we examined the retention time of samples (including the blank and standard samples used as control). For example, Figure 1 shows the retention time of compound Kynurenine, no large variation was observed (gray solid line indicates the average of retention time over measurements and two dashed lines indicate +5% and -5% deviation). 2. Limits of detection (LOD)

By comparing the calculated concentration to the real concentration of standard compounds, as well as taking into account the fitness of regression, we determined the upper and lower limits of detection (LOD) for each compound. Below we show the distribution of samples (in blue) compared to standards (gold) with different concentrations and blank samples (in purple). The salmon dash line indicates the lower LOD of corresponding compounds, indicated by R-squared value changes in regression. Shapes of data points corresponding to the signal-to-noise ratio, above (triangle) or below (circle) the threshold (S/N = 10). 3. Data normalization

Probabilistic quotient normalization (pqn) was implemented (Dieterle F 2006) to normalize the concentration of samples. A random sample was chosen as the reference sample. The ratios between all other samples and the reference sample for all compounds were computed and the median value was extracted as the normalization factor the sample. New columns named Factor_pqn and Calculated_concentration_reNorm_pqn were added, indicating the computed normalization factor for each sample and the concentration of compounds after the pqn normalization, respectively.

Attention:

Please think carefully if pqn normalization is suitable for your project and decide if the original or normalized calculated concentration should be used for further analysis (Table S2).

Material and methods

Measured on: 7.11.2023
Internal method designation: 20231107_AA_3min
Methods are modified from previous publication (Mlleder M 2016).

Sample preparation

Supenatant samples were collected by Sonja. 80ul of a 10x dilution in water was prepared and 120ul of extraction buffer (1:1 MeOH:ACN + 20uM of each donepizil, caffeine, amoxicillin, ibuprofen) was added, followed by brief mixing and incubation at 4C for 30minutes. The extract was cleared by centrifugation (4C, 3200g, 5min) and the supernatant was transferred to a fresh PCR plate for analysis. Standard series was prepared in water. 0.25ul of internal standard dissolved in water containing labelled compounds was coinjected with each sample. Contains:

Sodium pyruvate 13C3 - 200uM
Succinic acid 13C4 - 100uM
Arginine 13C6 - 50uM
Glutamine 13C5 - 50uM
Citric acid 13C6 - 100uM
Lysine 13C6 - 50uM

LC-MS measurement

Mass spectrometer: Agilent triple quadrupole (QQQ) 6470 with JetStream ion source (AJS-ESI)
UPLC instrument: Agilent 1290 Infinity II
Acquisition scheme: dynamic (schedueled) MRM
Chromatography: Hydrophilic interaction liquid chromatography (HILIC)
Analytical Column: Waters Acquity BEH Amide 1.7 m, 2.1 mm X 100 mm
Column temperature: 35C
Needle wash: Water + 0.1% formic acid
Injection Volume: 0.25l
Buffer A: 50% acetonitrile, 10 mM ammonium formate, 0.176% formic acid
Buffer B: 95:5:5 acetonitrile:methanol:water, 10 mM ammonium formate, 0.176% formic acid
Flow rate: 0.9ml/min
Gradient: 0min:85%B, 0.7min:85%B, 2.55min:5%B, 2.9min:5%B, 2.91min:85%B, 3.5min:stoptime
Source parameters: Gas temp:325C, Gas flow:10 l/min, Nebulizer:40psi, Sheath gas temp:350C, Sheath gas flow:11 l/min, Capillary (positive):3500V, Capillary (negative):3500V, Nozzle voltage (positive):1000V, Nozzle voltage (negative):100V
Cycle time: 320ms

LC-MS data analysis

Acquisition software: MassHunter Workstation LC/MS Data Acquisition v10.1
Analysis software: MassHunter Workstation Quantitative Analysis for QQQ v10.1
We used customized R scripts (in ./scripts/ folder) for the pre-processing and visualization of data.
